Conclusions¶

Question 11: Write a short report explaining the pros and the cons of each methods that you implemented. 25% of the grade of this project will correspond to this question, thus, it should be done carefully. In particular, please add a plot that will summarize all your numerical results.

Report

In part 1, I remind the context as well as an important assumption I made in this TP.

In part 2, I remind the two solutions I proposed to get a more reliable training procedure evaluation (question 2).

In part 3, I study the pros and the cons of each method I implemented and experienced with.

In part 4, I discuss the obtained results and the possible paths of improvement.

Table summarizing the results is given at the bottom of this Jupyter Notebook.

1. Context

The goal of this practical was to train a supervised model using only $X_{train}$, the first 100 examples of the CIFAR10 training dataset. To develop the model, we could also dispose of $X$, the remaining 49900 samples of the CIFAR10 training set, but for which we hide the labels.

I assumed that we were not allowed to see $X_{test}$, the 10000 samples of CIFAR10 test set, when developping the model : thus we had to build our validation sets picking instances exclusively from the 100 first instances.

2. Solutions for a better training procedure evaluation question

Note : this part is essentially a repetition of my answer to question 2/11.

2.1. How to deal with the small size of the labelled training set for validation ?

In order to know when to stop the training (and to tune the hyperparameters), we need to split $X_{train}$ into a training dataset $D_{train}$ and a validation dataset $D_{val}$. As $|X_{train}|=100$, we are torn apart between keeping a large proportion of images in $X_{train}$ to predict better, and having a reasonably large $D_{val}$ to assess correctly the prediction accuracy of our model at a given time of the training.

I suggested to build not one but five models, each based on a different split of $|X_{train}|$ between $D_{train}$ (80%) and $D_{val}$ (20%). This way, I could make use of each of the 100 examples to make the prediction, and it became possible to have two examples per class in my validation set. When the classification model could assign probabilities for belonging to each class, I averaged the probabilities outputted by the 5 models to assign the final label. Actually, I followed this process of building 5 models with different splits 80%/20% for experiments A and B only (see the table in section 4. for meanings of the letters). For experiments C,D, E, and F, I built the model based on the first split 80%/20% only (for computation times economy).

2.2. How to deal with the unbalanced classes in the labelled training set ?

In addition, the number of examples per class in $X_{train}$ varies much between classes in $X_{train}$ (16 examples for the largest class, 4 for the smallest). If we have a unbalanced set $D_{train}$, this is prone to lead to bias in the predictions. While if $D_{val}$ is unbalanced, our model assessment will not be reliable.

To ensure that the training set and that the validation set are balanced : 1) I first built the validation set $D_{val}$, by picking at random two examples per class. 2) Then, to ensure the training set $D_{train}$ in balanced, I replicated $\max_{0 \leq j \leq 9} |C_j| -|C_i|$ examples from class $C_i$, where $|C|$ denotes the number of examples in class $C$ in $D_{train}$. I preferred oversampling the smallest classes (adding replicated examples) to undersampling the largest classes (remvoving examples) as our training set is already very small. Another solution to remove the bias could have consisted in dividing the model output probabilities of belonging to each class by the prior probabilites (ie. the number of instances per class in the training set).

3. Methods, results, pros and cons

3.1. Training CNNs (ResNet, VGG) from scratch

First method we considered is to train Convolutional Neural Networks from scratch, ie. begininning with a random initialization of the weights and using only instances from $D_{train}$ for training.

We tried two types of CNN :

  • ResNet-18, a residual network with 18 layers.

  • VGG, which essentially uses 33 convolutional layers stacked on top of each other, with max-pooling layers reducing volume size with depth increasing. We tried different architectures/depths for VGG, with 11, 13, 16 and 19 layers.

I optimized the weights thanks to Stochastic Gradient Descent, using a learning rate of 0.01, a momentum of 0.9, and fixing the maximum number of epochs to 10 (with early stopping policy : stop after 5 epochs without decrease of the validation loss, and we kept the weights associated to the lowest validation loss for predictions).

Results / Pros / Cons :

  • Best architecture seemt to be VGG-11, followed by ResNet-18. It seemt that VGG architectures with larger depths than 13 had too many parameters for the ressources we limited ourselves to (10 epochs), and on this small training set, overfitting might have happen if we had waited for more epochs.

  • Training neural networks from scratch on a small training set and with limited ressources seems possible when the architectures have a reasonable number of parameters. Obviously, there is a always a risk of overfitting.

  • In contrast, as we saw with VGG-N even with N>=16, it seems out of reach to train networks with a high depth with such small training set without any additional strategy such as data augmentation.

3.2. Transfer learning (without and with finetuning)

We then considered the transfer learning strategy. I resized the images from $32*32$ to $224*224$ and used a ResNet-18 architecture whose weights were already learnt on the ImageNet database.

More precisely, I considered two strategies :

  • 1) extract the images representations at the penultimate layer of the pre-trained network, and learn a simple classifier on these representations. This strategy simply amounts to changing the output dimension of the last linear layer of the original ResNet (for 10 output classes), and learn its weights with $D_{train}$ while freezing the weights of any other layer.
  • 2) fine-tune a part of a the pre-trained ResNet, from the top layer (with output dimension modified) up to the deepest layer of the network that my memory would enable me to (again by freezing all the weights upstream). I chose to privilege the highest layers for the fine-tuning as these are expected to learn the more specialized features, hence this is where we could gain the most for our specialized classification on CIFAR10. More precisely, I could finetune ResNet-18 from the 10th layer, ie. the two highest ResNet blocks, each of them composed of 2 convolutional layers with residual connections (256 maps with kernel size $3*3$, and 512 maps with kernel size $3*3$ respectively)

Results / Pros / Cons :

  • Transfer learning is very interesting here given the very small size of the training set and given the same type of objects featured by CIFAR10 and by ImageNet (on which was pre-trained the ResNet architecture we used). The features captured by the first layers of CNNs are always low-level and universal, but here we can even expect that the mid-level representations learnt on ImageNet are also interesting for our CIFAR10 classification task.

  • Strategy 1) (no-finetuning, linear classifier on the top of pre-trained embeddings) costs very little in terms of ressources. And it definitely improved the accuracies, compared to training the small ResNet-18 from scratch (from 21% to 54% in test accuracy).

  • Strategy 2), in which we additionnally finetuned the weights of the deepest layers (expected to learn the more specialized features), costs of course more but may appear more appealing in terms of accuracy. However, it did not improve performances in our experiments (only 51% in test accuracy). It is quite suprising, though we guess performances could be improved using a better optimization scheme and more epochs.

  • Finally, one hypothesis to explain the performances barrier of around 50% using transfer learning is that the resolutions of the CIFAR10 images and of the ResNet-18 are very different. One potentially interesting strategy to deal with that could consist in zooming/blurring the ImageNet images and pre-training the architecture with such blurred images (or, equivalently, reducing the size of the ImageNet images and pre-training the ResNet-18 architecture adequate for $32*32$ images used in question 3).

3.3. Semi-Supervised Learning : DCGAN features + Linear Classifier

Third method I used consists in learning a classifier, here a Support Vector Machine (with linear kernel), on the top of the embeddings learnt by the Discriminator of a GAN.

This is a Semi-Supervised Method as we do not make use only of the 100 labelled instances of $X_{train}$, but also of the unlabelled instances of $X$ to learn the unsupervised GAN Discriminator representations.

The chosen GAN architecture is caracterized by a noise dimension of 100 (space from which are generated the synthetic images) and by a discriminator embedding of dimension $64*8*2*2 = 2048$ (on which is applied the last convolutional layer and sigmoid for classification "real/synthetic").

I allowed two possibilities in the code:

  • either learning the weights of the GAN using a portion of the unlabelled examples $X$
  • or loading the pre-trained weights of the GAN on CIFAR training set (imported from https://github.com/csinva/pytorch_gan_pretrained/tree/master/cifar10_dcgan/weights). In the end I worked only with option (b) given our limited ressources.

I then computed the DCGAN features (discriminator embeddings) for all training labelled data, and learnt the Multi-Class SVM according to a One-Versus-Rest scheme, choosing the regularization weight C (penalty of an outlier) based on a log-scale grid search with simple validation.

Results / Pros / Cons :

This approach led to a better accuracy (30%) than training from scratch supervised CNN architectures (21-24%).

Learning an unsupervised representation of the images (thanks to the GAN Discriminator here) is definitely interesting as it allows to make a good use of unlabelled data.

However, training a GAN is a difficult task (cf. TP1 on Generative Modelling), and making it converge requires ressources. I did not succeed in this task, and that's why I used in the end an already pre-trained GAN on CIFAR training set.

3.4. Data Augmentation

Next strategy we tried consists in increasing the size of the training dataset, using various data augmentation strategies.

I applied at random various transformations "on the fly" to the selected batches. I tried:

  • translations and scalings with various zooms
  • rotations with angles in {0, 90, 180, 270}
  • color changes (brightness/contrast)
  • adding noise (gaussian blur and salt-and-pepper)

Results / Pros / Cons :

The data augmentation strategies I tried did not increase the accuracy, within the same number of epochs.

However, it theoretically remains an interesting strategy to reduce overfitting on larger architectures, with more capacity, provided that we have the computing ressources to train such deep networks. These transformed data indeed helps the network to learn useful invariances.

Last, combining transfer learning with data augmentation on ImageNet images, applying strong blur for instance, would have maybe been more relevant here (given the low resolution of CIFAR10 images).

3.5. Using Scattering Transform

Next, I tried applying the Scattering Transform to the training images and used the ResNet architecture described in https://arxiv.org/pdf/1703.08961.pdf appropriate for the new input.

Results / Pros / Cons :

Contrary to the data augmentation strategies defined in 3.4, applying the Scattering Transform led to an increase in test accuracy (from 21% to 27%). There are certainly much more investigations to do regarding parameters tuning and optimizers, since the article reported 38% accuracy using a CIFAR training set of 100 images.

The Scattering Transform is helpful, as it incoporates geometrical invariants in an unsupervised way. As we do not know all sources of variabilities for CIFAR natural images, the Scattering Transfrom should potentially help the network to learn richer invariances than the ones we manually defined in 3.4.

3.6. Weakly-Supervised Learning : Weak Labels from kNN on DCGAN features + ResNet Predictor of Weak Labels

The Weakly Supervised Learning strategy I implemented is the following :

I first trained a Nearest-Neighbor classifier based on the DCGAN features to get weak labels for the unlabelled data, ie. an estimated probability for each unlabelled data to belong to each class. I selected the number of nearest neighbors with simple validation.

I then considered two options to train a ResNet-18 architecture :

1) (preferred) we predict the soft labels, ie :

  • one-hot encodings of true labels (for labelled training data)
  • and weak labels assigned by the Nearest-Neighbor classifier (for unlabelled data).

2) or we predict the hard labels : true labels of labelled data, and most likely labels of unlabelled data

Results / Pros / Cons :

Both strategies hurted a lot the performances, even adding only 100 unlabelled data to the 100 training labelled data. To make better use of the unlabelled data, it would have been maybe more fruitful to infer weak labels from a better unsupervised representation than DCGAN features.

4. Results summary with table

In conclusion, it appears first that, on this very small training dataset, Transfer Learning leads to the highest gain in accuracy (with respect to training CNN from scratch) and without much effort. However, fine-tuning was not of precious help here. Last, we think that performances could have been even increased if pre-training a ResNet with blurred/smaller ImageNet images (to get closer to the CIFAR10 resolution).

Semi-Supervised Learning, which consisted here in learning an SVM classifier on the top of DCGAN unsupervised representation, appears as the second most promising solution (given the very large size of the unlabelled dataset $X$).

Our experiments with Scattering Transform showed a gain in accuracy (but not as important as the one we could have expected according to https://arxiv.org/pdf/1703.08961.pdf). Unsupervised incorporation of geometrical invariants was definitely more efficient than supervised Data Augmentation which did not enhance performances.

Finally, Weakly-Supervised Learning was not succesfull. Having better unsupervised representations than DCGAN features to assign better weak labels for unlabelled data would have been useful.
